non ius «1101, non iudicia fleri ι ‘ no judgments were given, no trials held‚’ a comprehensive phrase expressing that the whole machinery of the law was at a standstill. lus refers more particu- larly to civil suits, iudicia to crimiual trials, for which we have below causarum aeque iuris.

Ius dicere was the technical phrase by which the praetor was said to deliver judicial decisions by virtue of his authority (iurisdictio). In civil suits the praetor, after holding a preliminary inwstigation, usually appointed a iudex to hear the case : all proceedings before the praetor were called proceedings in iure, and those before the index were termed in iudicio.
